 tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCan we address the issue of nationalism without polemics and restore it to the domain of social science? Claudio Lomnitz-Adler takes a major step in that direction by applying anthropological tools to the study of national culture. His sweeping and innovative interpretation of Mexican national ideology constructs an entirely new theoretical framework for the study of national and regional cultures everywhere. With an analysis of culture and ideology in internally differentiated regional spaces—in this case Morelos and the Huasteca in Mexico—Exits from the Labyrinth links rich ethnographic and historical research to two specific aspects of Mexican national ideology and culture: the history of legitimacy and charisma in Mexican politics, and the relationship between the national community and racial ideology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural pluralismxHistoryx20th centuryxMexico. 0aCultural pluralismzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aEthnicityxHistoryx20th centuryxMexico. 0aEthnicityzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalismxHistoryx20th centuryxMexico. 0aNationalismzMexicoxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a20th century mexico.  aanthropology books.  aanthropology students.  acultural identity.  acultural studies.  aethnographic analysis.  ahistory of mexico.  ahuasteca.  alatin america.  alatin american history.  alatin american studies.  amexican anthropology.  amexican culture.  amexican history.  amexican ideology.  amexican nationalism.  amexican nationality.  amexican politics.  amexican village life.  amexico ethnography.  amexico studies.  amorelos.  a